data.content:
Your assertions work but `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages (just "expected True, was False"). MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions with clear diagnostics:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);                          // was: Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));         // no built-in "all match" — IsTrue is fine here
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);                         // was: Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users); // or just:
    // Assert.IsNotNull(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(list)` | Says "collection was empty" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, list)` | Says "expected 3, got 5" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` | Says "value was null" on failure |

Other useful collection assertions: `Assert.Contains(item, collection)`, `Assert.DoesNotContain(item, collection)`, `Assert.ContainsSingle(collection)` (returns the single element), and `Assert.IsEmpty(collection)`.

These require **MSTest 3.x+** (`MSTest` or `MSTest.Sdk` package).
